'''Acoustic foam''' is an open celled [[foam]] used for [[acoustic treatment]]. It attenuates airborne [[sound waves]] by increasing air resistance, thus reducing the [[amplitude]] of the waves.
<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.universalpowerconversion.com/acoustical-foam|title= Acoustical Foam|website= universalpowerconversion.com}}</ref> The energy is dissipated as [[heat]].{{cn|date=January 2017}} Acoustic foam can be made in several different colors, sizes and thickness.{{cn|date=January 2017}}

Acoustic foam can be attached to walls, ceilings, doors, and other features of a room to control noise levels, vibration, and echoes.{{cn|date=January 2017}}

Many acoustic foam products are treated with [[dye]]s and/or [[fire retardant]]s. <ref>{{Cite web |url= https://www.auralex.com/tools/testing-data/fire-testing-data/ |title= Fire Testing Data |website= auralex.com}}</ref>

== Uses ==
The objective of acoustic foam is to improve the sound quality by removing residual sound in any space.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chen|first=Francine Robina|date=1980|title=Acoustic characteristics and intelligibility of clear and conversational speech at the segmental level.|url=|journal=|volume=|pages=|via=Massachusetts Institute of Technology}}</ref>This purpose requires strategic placement of acoustic foam panels on walls, ceiling and floors, effectively eliminating [[Acoustic resonance|resonance]] within the room.<ref>{{Cite web |url= http://www.avbend.com/acoustic-treatment |title= Acoustic Treatment - Acoustic Panels |agency= Audio Visual Bend |website= avbend.com}}</ref>
=== Acoustic enhancement ===
The objective is to enhance the properties of sound by improving speech clarity and [[sound quality]].{{cn|date=January 2017}} For this reason, acoustic foam is often used in [[recording studio]]s.{{cn|date=January 2017}} The purpose is to reduce, but not entirely eliminate, resonance within the room.{{cn|date=January 2017}} This is achieved by placing similar sized pieces of foam, often in the shape of cones or triangles, on opposite walls.{{cn|date=January 2017}}

=== Functionality ===
Acoustic foam is a lightweight material made from polyurethane foam either polyether or polyester, and also extruded [[melamine foam]].{{cn|date=January 2017}} It is usually cut into tiles - often with pyramid or wedge shapes - which are suited to placing on the walls of a recording studio or a similar type of environment to act as a sound absorber, thus enhancing the sound quality within a room.{{cn|date=January 2017}}

Acoustic foam reduces or eliminates echoes and background noises by controlling the [[reverberation]] that sound can make by bouncing off walls.{{cn|date=January 2017}} This type of sound absorption is different from soundproofing, which is typically used to keep sound from escaping or entering a room.{{cn|date=January 2017}} Therefore, acoustic foam is installed in large rooms like churches, synagogues, concert halls.{{cn|date=January 2017}} These rooms have large, flat space and noise will certainly bounce around in the room.{{cn|date=January 2017}} These sound absorbers are used to improve the acoustics of the room, which thereby reduces noise in the room.{{cn|date=January 2017}}

Acoustic foam typically deals more with the mid and high frequencies.{{cn|date=January 2017}} To deal with lower frequencies, much thicker pieces of acoustic foam are needed; large pieces of acoustic foam are often placed in the corners of a room and are called acoustic foam corner [[bass trap]]s.{{cn|date=January 2017}}

